03933nam a22005175i 9780773569584DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735695847 a10.1515/97807735695842doi  a(DE-B1597)655983  a(OCoLC)1394872147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1054.5.M89bE534 2001eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a971.4/28031 aGordon, Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Public Pasts :bThe Contested Terrain of Montreal's Public Memories, 1891-1930 /cAlan Gordon. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (288 p.) :bIllustrations, maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Quebec/Études d'histoire du Québec ;v1400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface: Two Founding Peoples -- tAcknowledgements -- tExploring the Boundaries of Public Memory -- tCrossroads: Montréal to 1891 -- tGrounds For Disagreement: Social and Political Contexts of Montréal, 1891–1930 -- tFissured Heritage Elites -- tBritish Citizenship: Material Progress, Class Harmony, and Imperial Greatness -- tDevotion and Rebellion: The Contest for French Canada’s Public Memory -- tContested Terrain, Contiguous Territory -- tPublic Memory on the Move: Festivals and Parades -- tThe Angel of History -- tPostscript: The Reconquest of Montréal’s Memory -- tNotes -- tBibliographical Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGordon shows that while individual memory is crucial to establishing and maintaining identity, public memory is contested terrain - official customs and traditions, monuments, historic sites, and the celebration of anniversaries and festivals serve to order individual and collective perceptions of the past. Public memory is therefore the product of competitions and ideas about the past that are fashioned in a public sphere and speak primarily about structures of power. It conscripts historical events in a bid to guide shared memories into a coherent narrative that helps individuals negotiate their place in broader collective identities. The contest over public memories involves an exclusiveness that packages "others" according to the ideological preferences of the dominant cultures. Gordon shows that in Montreal ethnic, class, and gender voices strove to stake their own claims to legitimacy. Rather than acknowledging a single past, Montreal's many publics made and celebrated many public memories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356958440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773569584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773569584/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles